			h2 Frequency lists
			
			p From the previous figures one can derive how many words of each type one should learn to reach a certain level. There are some correlations between the extent of one's vocabulary and the overall dominance of the  (see for example <a href="https://universeofmemory.com/how-many-words-you-should-know/">https://universeofmemory.com/how-many-words-you-should-know/</a>).
			
			p Here are the list of most frequent words for each type:
			
			ul
				li verbs (<a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frankovacevich/grand_dictionary_ipy_notebook/master/most_frequent/Verb.html">download</a>)
				li adjectives and adverbs (<a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frankovacevich/grand_dictionary_ipy_notebook/master/most_frequent/AdjectiveAdverb.html">download</a>)
				li nouns (<a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/frankovacevich/grand_dictionary_ipy_notebook/master/most_frequent/Noun.html">download</a>)
				
			p For the verbs list, the verbs have been grouped by stem, which makes it easier to learn. They have also been paired with their corresponding perfective or imperfective form (with the imperfective form usually in italics). To learn more you can read the repository (indicated above).
			
			p In some cases I added a "!" sign to indicate that the word can be irregular. Nouns that have an unexpected gender have also been indicated.
			
